title: Simple trend decomposition — decomp
text: function simple wrapper decompose function.  decompose function separates time series additive multiplicative components describing trend, cyclical variation (e.g., daily annual), remainder.  additive decomposition assumes cyclical component time series stationary (.e., variance constant), whereas multiplicative decomposition accounts non-stationarity.  default, moving average symmetric window used filter cyclical component.  Alternatively, vector filter coefficients reverse time order can supplied (see decompose). decompose function requires ts object specified frequency.  decomp function converts input swmpr vector ts object prior decompose.  requires explicit input defining frequency time series required complete full period parameter.  example, frequency parameter diurnal periodicity 96 time step 15 minutes (24 hours * 60 minutes / 15 minutes).  frequency parameter annual periodicity 15 minute time step 35040 (365 days * 24 hours * 60 minutes / 15 minutes).  simplicity, chr strings 'daily' 'annual' can supplied place numeric values.  starting value time series must supplied latter case.  Use setstep function required standardize time step prior decomposition. Note decompose function relatively simple approach alternative methods investigated sophisticated decomposition desired.

text: data.frame daily integrated metabolism estimates returned. swmpr object passed function, data.frame added metab attribute original object returned.  See examples retrieval swmpr object.  metabolism data.frame contains following: date metabolic day, defined 24 hour period starting sunrise (calculated using metab_day) DOF_d Mean flux day hours, mmol m-2 hr-1. Day hours calculated using metab_day function. D_d Mean air-sea gas exchange day hours, mmol m-2 hr-1 DOF_n Mean flux night hours, mmol m-2 hr-1 D_n Mean air-sea gas exchange night hours, mmol m-2 hr-1 Pg Gross production, mmol m-2 d-1, calculated ((DOF_d - D_d) - (DOF_n - D_n)) * day hours Rt Total respiration, mmol m-2 d-1, calculated (DOF_n - D_n) * 24 NEM Net ecosytem metabolism, mmol m-2 d-1, calculated Pg + Rt

title: Ecosystem metabolism — ecometab
text: Input data include water quality weather time series, typically collected independent instrument systems.  SWMP data, requires merging water quality meteorology swmpr data objects using comb function (see examples).  default method using SWMP data, input data.frame must columns named datetimestamp (date/time column, POSIXct object), do_mgl (dissolved oxygen, mg/L), depth (depth, m), atemp (air temperature, C), sal (salinity, psu), temp (water temperature, C), wspd (wind speed, m/s), bp (barometric pressure, mb). open-water method common approach quantify net ecosystem metabolism using mass balance equation describes change dissolved oxygen time balance photosynthetic respiration processes, corrected using empirically constrained air-sea gas diffusion model (see Ro Hunt 2006, Thebault et al. 2008).  diffusion-corrected flux estimates averaged separately day night time series. nighttime average flux used estimate respiration rates, daytime flux used estimate net primary production. generate daily integrated rates, respiration rates assumed constant hourly night time flux rates multiplied 24. Similarly, daytime flux rates multiplied number daylight hours, varies location time year, yield net daytime primary production. Respiration rates subtracted daily net production estimates yield gross production rates.  metabolic day considered 24 hour period sunsets two adjacent calendar days. Areal rates gross production total respiration based volumetric rates normalized depth water column sampling location, assumed well-mixed, sensor reflecting integrated processes entire water column (including benthos).  Water column depth calculated mean value depth variable across time series swmpr object.  Depth values floored one meter shallow stations 0.5 meters also added reflect practice placing sensors slightly bottom. user-supplied depth value can also passed depth_val argument, either single value repeated vector equal length number rows input data.  accurate depth value used acts direct scalar metabolism estimates. air-sea gas exchange model calibrated wind data either collected , adjusted , wind speed 10 m surface. metadata consulted exact height.  value can changed manually using height argument, passed calckl. minimum three records required day night periods calculate daily metabolism estimates.  Occasional missing values air temperature, barometric pressure, wind speed replaced climatological means (hourly means month) period record using adjacent data within month missing data. calculations within function done using molar units (e.g., mmol O2 m-3).  output can returned mass units setting metab_units = 'grams' (.e., 1mol = 32 g O2, multiplies estimates 32 g mol-1/1000 mg/g).  Input data must standard mass units (mg L-1). specific approach estimating metabolism open-water method described Caffrey et al. 2013 references cited therein.

title: Ecosystem metabolism — ecometab
text: Caffrey JM, Murrell MC, Amacker KS, Harper J, Phipps S, Woodrey M. 2013. Seasonal inter-annual patterns primary production, respiration net ecosystem metabolism 3 estuaries northeast Gulf Mexico. Estuaries Coasts. 37(1):222-241. Odum HT. 1956. Primary production flowing waters. Limnology Oceanography. 1(2):102-117. Ro KS, Hunt PG. 2006. new unified equation wind-driven surficial oxygen transfer stationary water bodies. Transactions American Society Agricultural Biological Engineers. 49(5):1615-1622. Thebault J, Schraga TS, Cloern JE, Dunlavey EG. 2008. Primary production carrying capacity former salt ponds reconnection San Francisco Bay. Wetlands. 28(3):841-851.
